John Edward: Language skills essential for world citizens
The independent schools in Scotland have excellent service in the field of academic excellence, and this has continued in 2018 with again a series of excellent exam results, and in addition individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other initiatives of the entire community.
With more than 30,000 students in Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best service to their students and parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their pupils for continuing and higher education, the career they choose and their place as world citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a tailor-made school curriculum, we see that modern languages remain popular and desired subjects exceptionally within schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to someone in a language they understand, you reach their head.
If you talk to him in his own language, you reach out to him.”
This is a powerful reminder that we can’t rely solely on English when we want to build relationships and a bond of trust with people from other countries.
From the recent exam results of this year, we can deduce that languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest success rates in independent schools.
In total, 68 percent of students who studied foreign languages achieved a high score.
The data, collected from 74 schools affiliated with SCIS, shows that 72 percent of students achieved a high score (‘A’) in Mandarin, while 72 percent of German students, 69 percent of French students and 63 percent of Spanish students also achieved an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as essential skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now valued as much as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent school programs and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the British Commission on Employment and Skills found that 17 percent of the barriers to filling vacancies were attributed to a lack of language skills, according to employers.
Thus, language skills are becoming increasingly important in preparing young people for their future careers.
With more and more vacancies requiring language skills, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future with such a skill for life.
Communicating directly with people from abroad automatically gives a multilingual person an edge over the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation. French was the only language that stands above the 10 percent, with a total of 15 percent.
This is why investing in language education is now important for today’s children.
Several languages, especially those of emerging economies, will provide children with a better chance of finding a meaningful job.
In Scotland, schools choose which languages they teach.
Some schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while other schools will teach languages that are most important to the UK when looking ahead to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interest, there will always be different languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers specializing in this area.
Scottish independent schools strive to provide a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills needed to succeed, regardless of the future.
It cannot be denied at present that languages in a global business environment remain vital to the future of the country, so this should be reflected in education.
Modern languages should actually be considered as ‘international communication skills.’
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
We have to do it right.
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
