Harvard students take a course on the importance of adequate rest
A new course at Harvard University this year ensures that all students get more sleep, in an effort to combat the growing macho culture in which it seems cool to study all night long and drink a lot of caffeine.
One professor noted that students at the world’s largest university often have no idea of the basic principles of caring for themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School, a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, set up the course. To the best of his knowledge, this is unique in the United States.
He got the idea to start the course after giving a speech on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end of my speech, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why am I hearing this now, in my final year?’
She said no one had ever told her how important sleep is, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, which will be organized for the first time this year, will explain to students the basics of how good sleep habits help improve academic and athletic performance and how they also promote their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and the university’s executive director of health services, said the university decided to organize the course when it was found that students had a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The course lasts one hour and includes a range of interactive tasks.
In one of the sections, the students see an image of a dorm room, where they click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise equipment and books to learn more about the effects of caffeine and light and the way sports performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and the importance of a sleep routine.
In another section, participants get to hear how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
Using a map of the campus, with interactive icons, participants are encouraged to think about their daily routine.
“We know that this will not change the behavior of the students immediately.
But we think they have the right to know all this, just as people have the right to know what the consequences of choosing cigarettes have on their health, Czeisler added.
The culture of pride in one night’s study still exists, he says, and due to modern technology and the increasing pressure on students, lack of sleep is an increasing problem.
Ensuring enough sleep, of good quality, should be the student’s ‘secret weapon’ to fight stress, fatigue, and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid weight gain, because lack of sleep causes the brain to give them a constant feeling of hunger.
