Red light update: Concentrations drop in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota provinces
The latest report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission shows a general decline in concentrations of Red Lightning in parts of the Tampa Bay Area (located on the west coast of Florida in the United States).
According to the commission, there is reported fragmentary increase of the Red Light in the provinces of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, which could indicate a decrease in concentrations.
The Red Lightning extends over an average of 200 km of coastline, from northern Pinellas to southern Lee counties.
There are about 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County spots to be seen, but in fewer places than last week.
Red light has also been seen in Pasco County.
Mid-range concentrations have been reported for the coast of Pinellas County over the past week, low to high concentrations for the coast of Hillsborough County, background to high concentrations in Manatee County, background to high concentrations at or off the coast of Sarasota County, background to high concentrations at lae-to-high concentrations in Collier County, Charlotte County.
There are ongoing reports of airway irritation in the provinces of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier.
In northwest Florida, no reports of airway irritation have been reported in the past week.
